d.    When she finished asking, I told her it can‚Äôt burt to ask and that I knew the perfect person to help. When I found you and explained the request you didnt hesitate to say you would try. As Simone‚Äôs session began, you calmy sat down and handed me the signed yearbook, as if you hadn‚Äôt just created a miracle for this mom amd her daughter.  As soon as the session ended I reached out to the mom. As she approached me I could already see the tears in her eyes. We shared a few watery eyed hugs. She asked if she could thank you (which is where I sneakily captured this picture and video). Her words were ‚ÄúI couldn‚Äôt be more thankful!‚Äù  ‚ÄúMy daughter‚Äôs mind is going to be blown (8 year old daughter had already asked dad to call mom and check in). She also indicated she had made the mistake of only buying a day pass and would be attending the entire conference next year. She shared that her colleague almost moved her family vacation so she could attend this year, because that is how much she loves Workhuman Live. I love that you closed the conversation by sharing where the conference would be next year and selling her on WHL in Dublin. But most of all I love that you helped create a ‚Äúpeak‚Äù moment (per Dan Heath) that this mom (Melissa Parks) will never forget! Thank you for representing what it looks like to work human!\n\n127#Setting the Stage Like a Pro|To our amazing group of humans who took the stage to announce each WHL breakout speaker - BRAVO!!! This role required poise, prep, guts (especially for anyone not used to big audience public speaking), and energy - engaging the audience and setting the stage for the speaker talent. No small feat! Amy kicked us off by introducing Priya Parker on Monday afternoon and when her heel stuck in the stage floor, she handled it like the pro that she is and showed us all \"how it's done\" with grace and humanity. Everyone truly stepped up (yes, pun intended) for last-minute fill-ins when needed, seizing new opportunities and rising to the occasion. Thank you all for your collaboration and flexibility, and for truly making the breakout experience so phenomenal!\n\n128#An unstoppable duo!|Wow! Wow! Wow! Amy and Jenna - first, thank you for being the best humans in general. Second - thank you both for taking me in and letting me learn, grow, and laugh with you. Third - thank you for elevating the WH brand, both at WHL and every other day of the year. As we continue to grow as a company I cannot wait to see the amazing work you continue to do to make Workhuman a household name.\n\n129#What a line up!|The first live event in 3 years, brand new to the team, major staffing changes, major keynote changes, and so many more obstacles in your way. You both ran nearly 60 speaking sessions as if none of that even existed. You stayed calm, executed plan Bs as if they were plan As, and delivered world-class content to 1,500 people. It was a master class in running a speaking program!\n\n130#The Me for the We|Congratulations on a remarkable WHL Atlanta! Transparently, I struggled with this recognition as no amount of words would accurately summarize how I feel about each and every one of you. So, I‚Äôll keep it short. Good teams become great ones when the members trust each other enough to surrender the Me for the We. Your leadership throughout the planning and execution of WHL Atlanta was on show in full force and everyone was witness to its greatness. Your impact on the Workhuman business is immeasurable. Your collaboration and communication in good and tough times were timely and evident. Your impact on 1,500+ people was visibly life-changing (evident from ‚Äúugly cries to ugly laughs‚Äù and the glowing smiles throughout the event).   In the famous words of Nelson Mandela, ‚ÄúIt always seems impossible until it‚Äôs done!‚Äù I'm super proud of you.\n\n131#So much to say, so this is for being awesome!|Amy,  What a month! First, that Gallup survey! Wow! The fact that Fortune picked this up